<HEADLINE>
JANUARY-MARCH REGULAR EARNINGS UP 1.4% YEAR-ON-YEAR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 22 (CNA) 05/22/07  20:17:16 (By Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
Regular monthly earnings per employee in Taiwan's industrial  and
service sectors posted a year-on-year increase of 1.4 percent in
the first quarter of this year, the highest growth rate for the
same period of the last six years, according to tallies released
Tuesday by the Directorate General of Budget, Accounting and
Statistics (DGBAS).
</P>
<P>
Regular monthly earnings averaged NT$36,399 (US$1,090) between
January and March, DGBAS officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials noted that as of March, regular monthly earnings
had registered a year-on-year increase of more than 1 percent for
the 10th consecutive month.
</P>
<P>
In March, monthly earnings (including regular and non-regular
incomes) averaged NT$40,070, up 1.55 percent from the same month
of last year but down 47.91 percent from February, when workers
received their year-end bonuses, they said.
</P>
<P>
For the three months to March,  monthly earnings averaged
NT$55,529, for an increase of 1.73 percent year-on-year, they
said.
</P>
<P>
DGBAS tallies show that the number of employees in the industrial
and service sectors totaled 6.092 million as of the end of March,
up 10,000, or 0.17 percent, month-on-month and 100,000 year-on-
year.
</P>
<P>
For  the  first  quarter  of this  year,  the number  of non-
agricultural employees averaged 6.092 million, up 99,000 or 1.66
percent year-on-year, DGBAS officials said.
</P>
<P>
The monthly hours of work for the industrial and service sectors
averaged 189.8 hours in March, up 55.2 hours month-on-month but
down 3.3 hours year-on-year, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter of this year, the monthly hours of work
averaged 170.9 hours, down 2.7 hours year-on-year, they said.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector's labor productivity for March dropped
12.07 percent month-on-month but rose 1.43 percent year-on-year,
while the sector's unit output labor cost for March declined
60.04 percent month-on-month but increased 1.32 percent year-on-
year, they said.
</P>
